<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,1725,2040]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Most specimens have been collected from leaf litter or moss, apart from one series from Karamea that were collected via soil washing (J. Nunn, pers. comm., 2017). Those from the Snares Islands have been collected from a variety of habitats. Two species have been collected in reasonable numbers from pitfall traps set in Takahe Valley, Fiordland during a period of 4 years indicating that species are habitat specialists, with one species at lower altitudes associated red tussock (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zotov" authorityYear="1963" box="[521,738,1869,1895]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Chionochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis box="[521,738,1869,1895]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Chionochloa rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and another at higher altitudes associated with snow tussock (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zotov" authorityYear="1963" baseAuthorityName="Petrie" box="[161,302,1905,1932]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Chionochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="teretifolia">
<emphasis box="[161,302,1905,1932]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">C. teretifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<taxonomicName box="[327,425,1905,1931]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1437,1725,2040]" lastBlockId="50.[151,1437,153,467]" lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
The reduced eyes, head elongated anterior to antennae forming a short muzzle, simple unexpanded 3rd tarsomere and distinct body form of 
<taxonomicName authority="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein, 2020" authorityName="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein" authorityYear="2020" box="[512,627,1977,2003]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Nanomela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[512,627,1977,2003]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Nanomela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will distinguish this genus from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1104,1274,1977,2003]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelinae</taxonomicName>
and renders it difficult to recognise as a member of this subfamily, for example it fails to identify from the key to subfamilies in Reid (2000). However the mouthparts, ventral thoracic, modifed male tarsal setae and genitalic characters are typical of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[218,391,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelinae</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein, 2020" authorityName="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein" authorityYear="2020" box="[400,515,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Nanomela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[400,515,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Nanomela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1876" box="[860,949,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aphilon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[860,949,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Aphilon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which also has clavate or clubbed antennae, but 
<taxonomicName authority="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein, 2020" authorityName="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein" authorityYear="2020" box="[195,310,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Nanomela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[195,310,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Nanomela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from it by the elliptical body 
<taxonomicName box="[736,839,225,251]" form="and" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" rank="form">form and</taxonomicName>
reduced eyes. 
<taxonomicName authority="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein, 2020" authorityName="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein" authorityYear="2020" box="[1010,1125,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Nanomela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1010,1125,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Nanomela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1876" box="[1182,1271,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aphilon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1182,1271,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Aphilon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the head scarcely visible in dorsal view, subcoxal lines parallel to the coxal cavity on abdominal ventrite 1, and relatively flattened tibiae, characters which are also present to some degree in 
<taxonomicName authority="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein, 2020" authorityName="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein" authorityYear="2020" box="[877,991,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Maurodus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[877,991,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Maurodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein, 2020" authorityName="Leschen &amp; Reid &amp; Nadein" authorityYear="2020" box="[1005,1119,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Zeaphilon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="nov. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1005,1119,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Zeaphilon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and most 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1886" box="[1242,1394,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Caccomolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1242,1394,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Caccomolpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,153,467]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,333,359]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name is derived from “nanos” (ancient Greek—dwarf, midget) and “- 
<emphasis box="[1270,1324,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">mela</emphasis>
”, body, a common ending in the names of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[521,691,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelinae</taxonomicName>
genera. The new genus contains some of the smallest members of the subfamily worldwide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,858,440,467]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,153,467]" box="[199,858,440,467]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,440,467]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Distribution.</emphasis>
South Island, Stewart Island, Snares Islands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
